the problem is that --chaos-parameters-dictionary is actually a list of 
{
  key: string,
  value: ChaosParameters
}
and ChaosParameters itself is really big. I can't really think of how to structure a command to take that in as multiple parameters. It wouldn't really make sense to have a parameter for each item in the list when you don't know how many items could be in the list.

I don't think this `strides[0] == sizeof(T)` requirement is desirable: it should be easy enough to support arbitrary strides, which let slices (e.g. single rows/columns of numpy matrices) work as vector buffer inputs.  Something like this (untested) as a replacement for the Vector constructor ought to work:

```C++
new (&vec) Vector();
vec.reserve(info.shape[0]);
for (void *ptr = info.ptr, void *end = info.ptr + info.strides[0] * info.shape[0]; ptr != end; ptr += info.strides[0])
    vec.push_back(*static_cast<T *>(ptr));
```

(A small test to see that this really does work would be good as well).
